==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Æolipyle
<hw>⟦AE⟧*ol"i*pyle</hw> }</mhw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>aeolipilae</ets>;
<ets>Aeolus</ets> god of the winds + <ets>pila</ets> a ball, or Gr. <?/
gate (<it>i. e.</it>, doorway of ⟦AE⟧olus); cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧olipyle</ets>.]</ety> <def>An apparatus consisting chiefly
of a closed vessel (as a globe or cylinder) with one or more projecting
bent tubes, through which steam is made to pass from the vessel, causing
it to revolve.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>eolipile</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Such an apparatus was first described by Hero of
Alexandria about 200 years <sc>b. c.</sc> It has often been called the
first steam engine.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>AEolotropic</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>aeolotropic</ent>⟦br⟧
